  <div class="box">
    <h3 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h3>

    <h4>Who made this?</h4>

    <p>
      This app is hand-crafted by @chancancode
      (<a href="https://twitter.com/chancancode" target="_blank" title="Follow me on Twitter"><i class="icon-twitter"></i></a>
      <a href="https://github.com/chancancode" target="_blank" title="Follow me on Github"><i class="icon-github"></i></a>)
      with love.
    </p>

    <h4>Why another Hacker News reader?</h4>

    <p>
      For the most part, it's because I enjoyed building it. I also wanted to
      build an open-source app to showcase how awesome Ember is, something I can
      point people to when I talk to them about the framework.
    </p>

    <p>
      It was also a vehicle for me to test out a few Ember hacks I had in mind
      for a while. See <a href="http://emberconf.com/speakers.html#gchan" target="_blank">my talk at EmberConf</a>
      for details (video available soon).
    </p>

    <h4>Are you stealing my data?</h4>

    <p>
      No. In fact, I didn't build or run any backend components for this app
      myself. The app communicates with Hacker News directly without involving
      any extenral API – it parses the markup locally within your browser. (The
      web version uses a <a href="https://cors-anywhere.herokuapp.com/" target="_blank">CORS proxy</a>
      due to browser restrictions, but it can only access public data.)
    </p>

    <h4>Where is the extension for browser X?</h4>

    <p>
      Currently, the browser extension is only available for Chrome. However, it
      should be trivial to port it to another browser, I just haven't had a
      chance to investigate it yet. (The core app itself is not Chrome-specific,
      so only <a href="https://github.com/chancancode/hn-reader/tree/master/chrome" target="_blank">a very small wrapper</a>
      needs to be ported.) If you figured out how package it for your favourite
      browser, please <a href="https://github.com/chancancode/hn-reader/pulls" target="_blank">send a pull request</a>!
    </p>

    <h4>How do I disable the browser extension?</h4>

    <p>
      You can toggle the extension on a per-tab basis by clicking the orange "H"
      icon in the address bar. Alternatively, you can append <code>?hn-reader=0</code>
      to any URL to temporarily supress the extension.
    </p>
